tional name for someone who kept and trained falcons (a common feudal service). Falconry was a tremendously popular sport among the aristocracy in medieval Europe, and most great houses had their falconers. The surname could also have arisen as a metonymic occupational name for someone who operated the siege gun known as a <i>falcon</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Falconer was born in 1270, in Thurcaston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Millicent. He died in 1311, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1270–1311":"1270–1311","1273–1311":"1273–1311","1295–1346":"1295–1346","1346":"1346","1311":"1311","1295":"1295","1273":"1273","1270":"1270","about 1295":"umbes 1295","Of Thurcaston, Leicestershire, England":"Thurcaston, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thurcaston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Thurcaston, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1270–1311":"1270–1311","1273–1311":"1273–1311","1295–1346":"1295–1346","1346":"1346","1311":"1311","1295":"1295","1273":"1273","1270":"1270","about 1295":"noin 1295","Of Thurcaston, Leicestershire, England":"Thurcaston, Leicestersh